1.1. A Note on Terminology:
{
    "1.1. A Note on Terminology": [
        {
            "Original": "For the purpose of exposition, the original Internet-standard Network Management Framework, as described in RFCs 1155 (STD 16), 1157 (STD 15), and 1212 (STD 16), is termed the SNMP version 1 framework (SNMPv1).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The current framework is termed the SNMP version 2 framework (SNMPv2).",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Overview -> 2.6. Transport Mappings:
{
    "2. Overview -> 2.6. Transport Mappings": [
        {
            "Original": "It is important to note that the exchange of SNMPv2 messages requires only an unreliable datagram service, with every message being entirely and independently contained in a single transport datagram.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Specific transport mappings and encoding rules are specified elsewhere [5\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "Specific transport mappings and encoding rules are specified elsewhere [5]."
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, the preferred mapping is the use of the User Datagram Protocol [6].",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Overview -> 2.4. Retransmission of Re:
{
    "2.4. Retransmission of Requests": [
        {
            "Original": "For all types of request in this protocol, the receiver is required under normal circumstances, to generate and transmit a response to the originator of the request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Whether or not a request should be retransmitted if no corresponding response is received in an appropriate time interval, is at the discretion of the application originating the request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This will normally depend on the urgency of the request.",
            "Adjusted": "The decision to retransmit a request will normally depend on the urgency of the request."
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, such an application needs to act responsibly in respect to the frequency and duration of re-transmissions.",
            "Adjusted": "However, the application originating the request needs to act responsibly in respect to the frequency and duration of retransmissions."
        }
    ]
}

2. Overview -> 2.2. Management Informati:
{
    "2. Overview -> 2.2. Management Information": [
        {
            "Original": "The term, variable, refers to an instance of a non-aggregate object type defined according to the conventions set forth in the SMI [2\"\")] or the textual conventions based on the SMI [3\"\")].",
            "Adjusted": "The term variable refers to an instance of a non-aggregate object type defined according to the conventions set forth in the SMI or the textual conventions based on the SMI."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The term, variable binding, normally refers to the pairing of the name of a variable and its associated value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, if certain kinds of exceptional conditions occur during processing of a retrieval request, a variable binding will pair a name and an indication of that exception.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A variable-binding list is a simple list of variable bindings.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The name of a variable is an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which is the concatenation of the OBJECT IDENTIFIER of the corresponding object- type together with an OBJECT IDENTIFIER fragment identifying the instance.",
            "Adjusted": "The name of a variable is an OBJECT IDENTIFIER which is the concatenation of the OBJECT IDENTIFIER of the corresponding object-type together with an OBJECT IDENTIFIER fragment identifying the instance."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The OBJECT IDENTIFIER of the corresponding object-type is called the OBJECT IDENTIFIER prefix of the variable.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

2. Overview -> 2.1. Roles of Protocol En:
{
    "2. Overview -> 2.1. Roles of Protocol Entities": [
        {
            "Original": "A SNMPv2 entity may operate in a manager role or an agent role.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A SNMPv2 entity acts in an agent role when it performs SNMPv2 management operations in response to received SNMPv2 protocol messages (other than an inform notification) or when it sends trap notifications.",
            "Adjusted": "A SNMPv2 entity acts in an agent role when the entity performs SNMPv2 management operations in response to received SNMPv2 protocol messages (other than an inform notification) or when the entity sends trap notifications."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A SNMPv2 entity acts in a manager role when it initiates SNMPv2 management operations by the generation of SNMPv2 protocol messages or when it performs SNMPv2 management operations in response to received trap or inform notifications.",
            "Adjusted": "A SNMPv2 entity acts in a manager role when the entity initiates SNMPv2 management operations by the generation of SNMPv2 protocol messages or when the entity performs SNMPv2 management operations in response to received trap or inform notifications."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A SNMPv2 entity may support either or both roles, as dictated by its implementation and configuration.",
            "Adjusted": "A SNMPv2 entity may support either or both roles, as dictated by the entity's implementation and configuration."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Further, a SNMPv2 entity can also act in the role of a proxy agent, in which it appears to be acting in an agent role, but satisfies management requests by acting in a manager role with a remote entity.",
            "Adjusted": "Further, a SNMPv2 entity can also act in the role of a proxy agent, in which the entity appears to be acting in an agent role, but satisfies management requests by acting in a manager role with a remote entity."
        }
    ]
}

2. Overview -> 2.3. Access to Management:
{
    "2. Overview -> 2.3. Access to Management Information": [
        {
            "Original": "Three types of access to management information are provided by the protocol.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "One type is a request-response interaction, in which a SNMPv2 entity, acting in a manager role, sends a request to a SNMPv2 entity, acting in an agent role, and the latter SNMPv2 entity then responds to the request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This type is used to retrieve or modify management information associated with the managed device.",
            "Adjusted": "This request-response interaction between manager and agent roles is used to retrieve or modify management information associated with the managed device."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A second type is also a request-response interaction, in which a SNMPv2 entity, acting in a manager role, sends a request to a SNMPv2 entity, also acting in a manager role, and the latter SNMPv2 entity then responds to the request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This type is used to notify a SNMPv2 entity, acting in a manager role, of management information associated with another SNMPv2 entity, also acting in a manager role.",
            "Adjusted": "This request-response interaction between manager roles is used to notify a SNMPv2 entity, acting in a manager role, of management information associated with another SNMPv2 entity, also acting in a manager role."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The third type of access is an unconfirmed interaction, in which a SNMPv2 entity, acting in an agent role, sends a unsolicited message, termed a trap, to a SNMPv2 entity, acting in a manager role, and no response is returned.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "This type is used to notify a SNMPv2 entity, acting in a manager role, of an exceptional situation, which has resulted in changes to management information associated with the managed device.",
            "Adjusted": "This unconfirmed interaction is used to notify a SNMPv2 entity, acting in a manager role, of an exceptional situation, which has resulted in changes to management information associated with the managed device."
        }
    ]
}

4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Common:
{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.1. Common Constructs": [
        {
            "Original": "The value of the request-id field in a Response-PDU takes the value of the request-id field in the request PDU to which it is a response.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "By use of the request-id value, a SNMPv2 application can distinguish the (potentially multiple) outstanding requests, and thereby correlate incoming responses with outstanding requests.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In cases where an unreliable datagram service is used, the request-id also provides a simple means of identifying messages duplicated by the network.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Use of the same request-id on a retransmission of a request allows the response to either the original transmission or the retransmission to satisfy the request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, in order to calculate the round trip time for transmission and processing of a request-response transaction, the SNMPv2 application needs to use a different request-id value on a retransmitted request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The latter strategy is recommended for use in the majority of situations.",
            "Adjusted": "The strategy of using a different request-id value on retransmitted requests is recommended for use in the majority of situations."
        },
        {
            "Original": "A non-zero value of the error-status field in a Response-PDU is used to indicate that an exception occurred to prevent the processing of the request.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In these cases, a non-zero value of the Response-PDU's error-index field provides additional information by identifying which variable binding in the list caused the exception.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "A variable binding is identified by its index value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The first variable binding in a variable-binding list is index one, the second is index two, etc.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "SNMPv2 limits OBJECT IDENTIFIER values to a maximum of 128 sub- identifiers, where each sub-identifier has a maximum value of 2**32- 1\\.",
            "Adjusted": "SNMPv2 limits OBJECT IDENTIFIER values to a maximum of 128 sub-identifiers, where each sub-identifier has a maximum value of 2^32-1."
        }
    ]
}

4. Protocol Specification -> 4.2. PDU Pr:
{
    "4. Protocol Specification -> 4.2. PDU Processing": [
        {
            "Original": "It is mandatory that all SNMPv2 entities acting in an agent role be able to generate the following PDU types: Response-PDU and SNMPv2- Trap-PDU; further, all such implementations must be able to receive the following PDU types: GetRequest-PDU, GetNextRequest-PDU, GetBulkRequest-PDU, and SetRequest-PDU.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "It is mandatory that all SNMPv2 entities acting in a manager role be able to generate the following PDU types: GetRequest-PDU, GetNextRequest-PDU, GetBulkRequest-PDU, SetRequest-PDU, InformRequest-PDU, and Response-PDU; further, all such implementations must be able to receive the following PDU types: Response-PDU, SNMPv2-Trap-PDU, InformRequest-PDU; In the elements of procedure below, any field of a PDU which is not referenced by the relevant procedure is ignored by the receiving SNMPv2 entity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, all components of a PDU, including those whose values are ignored by the receiving SNMPv2 entity, must have valid ASN.1 syntax and encoding.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "For example, some PDUs (e.g., the GetRequest-PDU) are concerned only with the name of a variable and not its value.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this case, the value portion of the variable binding is ignored by the receiving SNMPv2 entity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The unSpecified value is defined for use as the value portion of such bindings.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "On generating a management communication, the message \"wrapper\" to encapsulate the PDU is generated according to the \"Elements of Procedure\" of the administrative framework in use is followed.",
            "Adjusted": "On generating a management communication, the message wrapper to encapsulate the PDU is generated according to the Elements of Procedure of the administrative framework in use."
        },
        {
            "Original": "While the definition of \"max-bindings\" does impose an upper-bound on the number of variable bindings, in practice, the size of a message is limited only by constraints on the maximum message size -- it is not limited by the number of variable bindings.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "On receiving a management communication, the \"Elements of Procedure\" of the administrative framework in use is followed, and if those procedures indicate that the operation contained within the message is to be performed locally, then those procedures also indicate the MIB view which is visible to the operation.",
            "Adjusted": "On receiving a management communication, the Elements of Procedure of the administrative framework in use is followed, and if those procedures indicate that the operation contained within the message is to be performed locally, then those procedures also indicate the MIB view which is visible to the operation."
        }
    ]
}

2. Overview -> 2.5. Message Sizes:
{
    "2. Overview -> 2.5. Message Sizes": [
        {
            "Original": "The maximum size of a SNMPv2 message is limited to the minimum of: (1) the maximum message size which the destination SNMPv2 entity can accept; and, (2) the maximum message size which the source SNMPv2 entity can generate.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "The former may be known on a per-recipient basis; and in the absence of such knowledge, is indicated by transport domain used when sending the message.",
            "Adjusted": "The maximum message size which the destination SNMPv2 entity can accept may be known on a per-recipient basis; and in the absence of such knowledge, is indicated by transport domain used when sending the message."
        },
        {
            "Original": "The latter is imposed by implementation-specific local constraints.",
            "Adjusted": "The maximum message size which the source SNMPv2 entity can generate is imposed by implementation-specific local constraints."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Each transport mapping for the SNMPv2 indicates the minimum message size which a SNMPv2 implementation must be able to produce or consume.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Although implementations are encouraged to support larger values whenever possible, a conformant implementation must never generate messages larger than allowed by the receiving SNMPv2 entity.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "One of the aims of the GetBulkRequest-PDU, specified in this protocol, is to minimize the number of protocol exchanges required to retrieve a large amount of management information.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "As such, this PDU type allows a SNMPv2 entity acting in a manager role to request that the response be as large as possible given the constraints on message sizes.",
            "Adjusted": "As such, the GetBulkRequest-PDU type allows a SNMPv2 entity acting in a manager role to request that the response be as large as possible given the constraints on message sizes."
        },
        {
            "Original": "These constraints include the limits on the size of messages which the SNMPv2 entity acting in an agent role can generate, and the SNMPv2 entity acting in a manager role can receive.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "However, it is possible that such maximum sized messages may be larger than the Path MTU of the path across the network traversed by the messages.",
            "Adjusted": "However, it is possible that maximum sized messages may be larger than the Path MTU of the path across the network traversed by the messages."
        },
        {
            "Original": "In this situation, such messages are subject to fragmentation.",
            "Adjusted": "In this situation, messages larger than the Path MTU are subject to fragmentation."
        },
        {
            "Original": "Fragmentation is generally considered to be harmful [4], since among other problems, it leads to a decrease in the reliability of the transfer of the messages.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "Thus, a SNMPv2 entity which sends a GetBulkRequest-PDU must take care to set its parameters accordingly, so as to reduce the risk of fragmentation.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        },
        {
            "Original": "In particular, under conditions of network stress, only small values should be used for max-repetitions.",
            "Adjusted": "No change"
        }
    ]
}

